    {
        "content": "<p>Hello,</p>\n<p>I'm getting the error <code>invalid occurrence of universe level 'u_1'</code> when writing expressions that contain an empty list.<br>\nI'm able to prevent the error by writing a type assertion for the empty list, but I'd like to avoid this if possible.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">abbrev</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">length</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">([]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- this works, because there is a type assertion</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">abbrev</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">length</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">length</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[]</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- this fails with: invalid occurrence of universe level 'u_1'</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>The larger context is I'm teaching an intro to logic course to computer engineers and am trying to keep the syntax as simple as possible.  I'm happy to define my own <code>length</code> function that works only over <code>Type 0</code> types, if that's a route toward a solution.  (In this first offering of the course, I'm using Lean primarily for the students to write and typecheck logical expressions.  I'm not yet having the students prove theorems in Lean, so it's ok if I lose access to the List tactics.)</p>\n<p>I tried writing my own size function as:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">abbrev</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">size3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">::</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">size3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">abbrev</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">size3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>and got the error: <code>don't know how to synthesize implicit argument @size3 ?m.555 (@List.nil.{0} ?m.555)</code></p>\n<p>-mark</p>",
        "id": 479911191,
        "sender_full_name": "Mark Aagaard",
        "timestamp": 1730390586
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the point is that once again, lean can't figure out what <code>α</code> is. (i.e., lean is trying to figure out what the type of <code>[]</code> is, but gets stuck at <code>List ?A</code>)</p>",
        "id": 479911700,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730390739
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and btw, <code>α : Type</code> is a shortcut for <code>α : Type 0</code>, which you might find helpful in teaching.</p>",
        "id": 479911997,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730390813
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>for teaching, it might be helpful if you use <code>set_option autoImplicit false</code></p>",
        "id": 479912518,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730390957
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>this way, it becomes more obvious when you introduce type polymorphism</p>",
        "id": 479912597,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730390982
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you use any mathlib from this month, the error message is less obscure:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">abbrev</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">length</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">length</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[]</span>\n<span class=\"c\">/-</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">don't know how to synthesize implicit argument 'α'</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">  @List.length ?m.4210 []</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">-/</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>The universe level issue was the less-strong reason why the definition failed. The proximal reason is what Edward says, the type argument to <code>List.length</code> isn't able to be solved for.</p>",
